Lab Exercise 1: Introduction to estimating diversification rates

1. Lineage through time plots

In this tutorial, we will use phytools to create lineage-through-time (LTT) plots and compute the γ test statistic of Pybus & Harvey (2010).

To get started, let’s load phytools & dependencies and set the working directory (remember, you need to point to the appropriate directory on your computer).

library(phytools)
## Loading required package: ape
## Loading required package: maps
setwd("/Users/michael_alfaro/Dropbox/teaching/200a2016/lab-1-tree-sims/")

Next, let’s load a tree from file: etheostoma_percina_chrono.tre.

setwd("/Users/michael_alfaro/Dropbox/teaching/200a2016/lab-1-tree-sims/")
darter.tree<-read.tree("etheostoma_percina_chrono.tre")

Our tree is from Near et al. (2011). In it, they sampled 201 of 216 species from the group (93%) - but for the purposes of this exercise (and the next), we will assume 100% sampling.

Let’s first plot the tree:

plotTree(darter.tree,ftype="i",fsize=0.4,type="fan",lwd=1)

Now let’s use the function ltt in the phytools package to generate a LTT plot:

obj<-ltt(darter.tree,log.lineages=FALSE)

obj

Why are we getting an NA for gamma? Our tree is not fully birfucating But we can fix this….

plot(obj,log.lineages=FALSE,main="LTT plot for darters")

Here we plot the tree and the LTT plot together….

plot(obj,show.tree=TRUE,log.lineages=FALSE,main="LTT plot for darters")

Note that under pure-birth, the number of lineages should rise exponentially through time. By convention, and because it linearizes the expectation under pure-birth, we normally would plot our pure-birth trees on a semi-log scale, meaning that the vertical axis is on a log-scale while our horizontal axis is on a linear scale.

plot(obj,log.lineages=FALSE,log="y",main="LTT plot for darters",
    ylim=c(2,Ntip(darter.tree)))
## we can overlay the pure-birth prediction:
h<-max(nodeHeights(darter.tree))
x<-seq(0,h,by=h/100)
b<-(log(Ntip(darter.tree))-log(2))/h
lines(x,2*exp(b*x),col="red",lty="dashed",lwd=2)

We might like to compare the observed LTT, to simulated LTTs assuming a pure-birth process of the same duration & resulting in the same total number of species. We can do this using the phytools function pbtree:

trees<-pbtree(b=b,n=Ntip(darter.tree),t=h,nsim=100,method="direct",
    quiet=TRUE)
obj<-ltt(trees,plot=FALSE)
plot(obj,col="grey",main="LTT of darters compared to simulated LTTs")
lines(c(0,h),log(c(2,Ntip(darter.tree))),lty="dashed",lwd=2,col="red")
## now let's overlay our original tree
ltt(darter.tree,add=TRUE,lwd=2)

Alternatively, the function ltt95 gives a (1-α)% CI for the LTT based on a set of trees. We use it here using a simulated distribution of trees, but this might also be useful if we have, for example, a set of trees from the posterior distribution of a Bayesian analysis:

ltt95(trees,log=TRUE)
title(main="LTT of darters compared to simulated LTTs")
ltt(darter.tree,add=TRUE,log.lineages=FALSE,col="red",lwd=2)

2. Fitting pure birth and birth-death models to trees.

library(phytools)
fitbd <- birthdeath(darter.tree)

birthdeath() reports compund parameters, d/b (extinction fraction) and b-d (net diversification). To get the b and d rates separately we will use a phytools function, bd()

bd(fitbd)
##          b          d 
## 0.23619344 0.01495258

One problem with this function is that the birth and death rates are conditioned on full sampling of the tree. This is not the case for the darter tree but we will not pursue more appropriate rate estimatation here.

3. The γ-statistic

The γ statistic of Pybus & Harvey (2010) was designed to have a standard normal distribution for trees generated under a pure-birth speciation model. Let’s test this with our 100 simulated pure-birth phylogenies:

g<-sapply(trees,function(x) ltt(x,plot=FALSE)$gamma)
hist(g,main=expression(paste("Distribution of ",gamma," from simulation")))

mean(g)
## [1] 0.07115087
var(g)
## [1] 0.841266

We can test hypotheses about γ. This is done automatically with ltt. For example

obj<-ltt(darter.tree,plot=FALSE)
print(obj)
## Object of class "ltt" containing:
## 
## (1) A phylogenetic tree with 201 tips and 200 internal nodes.
## 
## (2) Vectors containing the number of lineages (ltt) and branching times (times) on the tree.
## 
## (3) A value for Pybus & Harvey's "gamma" statistic of 0.2007, p-value = 0.841.

Note that the p value returned by ltt() assumes that the tree is fully sampled. Is this the case for your tree?

Finally, let’s simulate a tree under a different model of lineage accumulation - the coalescent - and see what the result is. Theoretically, this should result in a significantly positive γ.

coal.tree<-rcoal(n=100)
plotTree(coal.tree,ftype="off")

obj<-ltt(coal.tree,log.lineages=FALSE,log="y")

darter.gamma <- obj$gamma # ltt returns a gamma value as one of its elements

Lets compare the mean gamma value of 200 pb trees to gamma from the coalescent tree.

trees<-pbtree(n=100,nsim=200,scale=max(nodeHeights(coal.tree)))
ltt95(trees,log=TRUE)
title(main="Simulated coalescent trees compared to pure-birth LTTs")
ltt(coal.tree,add=TRUE,log.lineages=FALSE,col="red",lwd=2,lty="dashed")

3. Incomplete sampling

The gamma value for the darter tree assumes that we have fully sampled the tree. In reality, the authors only sampled 201 of 216 species. How is incomplete sampling expected to affect the caluclation of gamma? Lets use the power of simulation to explore this. We will simulate pure birth trees that match the true clade size and then randomly prune the simulated trees down to match the number of taxa sampled in the empirical tree. We calculate gamma on each pruned tree. The resulting distribution represents the expected effect on gamma values that is due to incomplete sampling. If the observed gamma value from the tree falls into the tails of distribution we can conclude that the amount of node imbalance in the observed tree (the gamma value) is too extreme to be produced by incomplete sampling alone. If the observed gamma does not fall into the tails of this distribution, then the observed gamma respresents a value that could have been produced by a tree evolving under a constant rate that has been incompletey sampled. This is the MCCR test of Pybus and Harvey, 2000.

Here is a block of code that performs the MCCR test and demonstrates the utility of functions as well as the power of R–if you understand what the objective of a particular analysis is, you will be able to tailor functions to suit your needs instead of relying upon black box functions. To simulate trees we will use . We will use a purebirth estimate of the the tree based upon their total age and richness.

library(geiger)
age <- 25.91862
richness <- 216
darterbirth =  (log(richness) - log(2))/age
darterbirth
## [1] 0.1806474
richness <- 216
missing <- 15
#this simulates gamma values when trees are undersampled.
#we will grow trees with n=34 and prune them down to 13 taxa

num_simulations<-200 #number of simulations
g1_null<-numeric(num_simulations) #g1_null will hold the simulated gamma values
for(i in 1:num_simulations) {
  sim.bdtree(darterbirth, d=0, stop = "taxa", n=richness)->sim_tree 
  drop.random(sim_tree, missing)->prune # prune down to the # of taxa in the phylogeny
    gammaStat(prune)->g1_null[i]
}
# create a histogram of the null distribution
hist(g1_null)

#arrow indicates where the observed gamma falls in the null you just generated
arrows(darter.gamma, 40, darter.gamma, 0, col="red", lwd=2) 

# Which of the null values are smaller (more negative) than the data?
smallerNull<-g1_null<=darter.gamma
# How many TRUEs are there?
count<-sum(smallerNull)

# finally, what is the p-value?
mccr_pval<-(count+1)/(num_simulations+1)
mccr_pval
## [1] 1
